
[1]correlative

   CORRELATIVE, a. [L. Con and relativus. See Relate and Relative.] Having
   a reciprocal relation, so that the existence of one in a certain state
   depends on the existence of another; as father and son, husband and
   wife, are correlative terms. The term son is correlative to that of
   father.

   CORRELATIVE, n. That which is opposed to something else in a certain
   relation. The son is the correlative of his father. Darkness and light
   are correlatives. Rest is the correlative of motion.
